  \point at (0,0,0);
\end{tikzpicture}


        It appears that w is indeed contained in the span of the columns of A; in fact, we can see
        w = v_1 - v_2 \implies x = \vec{1 -1}.

Let us check our geometric answer by solving the matrix equation using row reduction.  We put the system into an augmented matrix and row reduce:
        \amat{2 1 1; -1 0 -1; 1 -1 2}
        \quad\xrightarrow{\text{RREF}}\quad
        \amat{1 0 1; 0 1 -1; 0 0 0}.

        This gives us x=1 and y=-1, which is consistent with the picture:
        1\vec{2 -1 1} -1\vec{1 0 -1} = \vec{1 -1 2}
        \sptxt{or}
        A\vec{1 -1} = \vec{1 -1 2}.

proof.p:
Now we show that 1 and 3 are equivalent.  (Since we know 1 and 2 are equivalent, this implies 2 and 3 are equivalent as well.)  If A has a pivot in every row, then its reduced row echelon form looks like this:
          \mat{
          1   0   \star,   0   \star ;
          0   1   \star , 0   \star ;
          0   0   0   1   \star
          },
          and therefore \amat{A b} reduces to this:
          \amat[c]{
          1   0   \star,   0   \star, \star ;
          0   1   \star , 0   \star, \star ;
          0   0   0   1   \star, \star
          }.
          There is no b that makes it inconsistent, so there is always a solution.  Conversely, if A does not have a pivot in each row, then its reduced row echelon form looks like this:
          \mat{
          1   0   \star,   0   \star ;
          0   1   \star , 0   \star ;
          0   0   0   0  0
          },
          which can give rise to an inconsistent system after augmenting with b:
          \amat{
          1   0   \star,   0   \star, 0 ;
          0   1   \star , 0   \star, 0 ;
          0   0   0   0   0 16
          }.
